From: Refracta user
Date: 2026-06-30
Subject: [PATCH v10] intro mode-fork: automated blank-disk vs custom (GUI)

Building on v1-v9, v10 makes the guided/expert division explicit in the GUI and
adds a fully automated blank-disk path, plus a guided-vs-encryption safeguard.

Installation-type dialog (right after the greeting):

  refractainstaller-gui now asks, up front:
    - "Automated btrfs install" - for a machine with a BLANK disk. Wipes one
      blank disk, builds the EFI + /boot + btrfs-subvolume layout automatically,
      and installs, skipping BOTH the expert-options screen and the partitioning
      screen. Requires a UEFI boot; refuses if there is no blank disk.
    - "Custom - all options" - the installer behaves exactly as before (manual
      partitioning / "Do not format", full expert options, the Partitioning
      page with its "Auto-create btrfs layout" and "Explain btrfs subvolumes"
      buttons).

Automated disk selection (guided_auto_setup):

  - exactly one blank disk        -> used automatically;
  - several disks, one blank      -> that blank disk used automatically;
  - more than one blank disk      -> the user picks from the blank disks.
  A blank disk = no partitions, no partition table, no filesystem signature; the
  live boot medium and mounted disks are always excluded. One confirmation, then
  the shared btrfs-disk-lib.sh partitions the disk and the guided variables are
  set so the rest of the install runs non-interactively (learns the manifest).
  In automated mode the "create an EFI partition" notice is also suppressed
  (the setup creates the ESP itself).

Guided-vs-encryption safeguard:

  If encryption (root or /home) was selected and the user then triggers a guided
  btrfs setup, the installer now REFUSES with an explanation instead of building
  an inconsistent layout (btrfs subvolumes/swap/hibernation are not set up on
  LUKS). Uncheck encryption for guided btrfs, or partition manually for ext+LUKS.

Refactor:

  guided_btrfs_setup (v9, Partitioning-page button) and the new guided_auto_setup
  share _guided_set_vars() so the pre-set variable contract lives in one place.

Changes from v9:
  - refractainstaller-yad: installation-type dialog (auto_mode); guided_auto_setup
    with blank-disk auto-selection; expert-options + partitioning screens skipped
    in automated mode; EFI-partition notice suppressed in automated mode;
    encryption-conflict refusal in guided setup; shared _guided_set_vars().
  - (refractainstaller CLI and btrfs-disk-lib.sh unchanged from v9.)

Files patched/added:
  usr/bin/refractainstaller-yad                    (GUI, 9.6.6)
  usr/bin/refractainstaller                        (CLI, 9.6.6; unchanged vs v8)
  usr/lib/refractainstaller/btrfs-disk-lib.sh      (shared library; unchanged vs v9)

Apply with:
  patch -p1 < btrfs-support-for-refractainstaller.patch

---

--- a/usr/bin/refractainstaller-yad
+++ b/usr/bin/refractainstaller-yad
@@ -52,6 +52,86 @@
 
 configfile="/etc/refractainstaller.conf"
 
+# btrfs subvolume layout.
+#
+# The installer LEARNS the real layout from the disk instead of hard-coding it:
+# the disk-setup script writes a small manifest at the btrfs top level
+# (subvolid=5), named by $btrfs_layout_manifest, with one TAB-separated
+# "<subvolume><TAB><mountpoint>" line per subvolume. load_btrfs_layout() reads
+# it into the arrays below, so ANY subvolume scheme works with no edits here.
+#
+# The arrays below are only the FALLBACK used when no manifest is present (e.g.
+# when formatting via the installer's own "btrfs (with subvolumes)" menu).
+btrfs_layout_manifest=".refracta-btrfs-layout"
+btrfs_subvols=( @rootfs @home @var @tmp @snapshots )
+btrfs_subvol_mounts=( "/" "/home" "/var" "/tmp" "/.snapshots" )
+btrfs_root_subvol="@rootfs"   # the subvolume mounted at "/" (overridden by manifest)
+btrfs_layout_source="default" # "manifest", "guessed", or "default" (for messages)
+
+# btrfs_guess_mount SUBVOL
+#   Best-effort mountpoint for a subvolume name when no manifest exists.
+#   Known names are mapped explicitly; unknown "@a_b_c" become "/a/b/c".
+btrfs_guess_mount () {
+	case "$1" in
+		@rootfs|@root|@)  echo "/" ;;
+		@home)            echo "/home" ;;
+		@snapshots)       echo "/.snapshots" ;;
+		@swap)            echo "/swap" ;;
+		@var)             echo "/var" ;;
+		@var_log)         echo "/var/log" ;;
+		@var_cache)       echo "/var/cache" ;;
+		@libvirt_images)  echo "/var/lib/libvirt/images" ;;
+		@tmp)             echo "/tmp" ;;
+		@opt)             echo "/opt" ;;
+		@srv)             echo "/srv" ;;
+		@*)               local _n="${1#@}" ; echo "/${_n//_//}" ;;
+		*)                echo "" ;;
+	esac
+}
+
+# load_btrfs_layout DEVICE
+#   Learn the btrfs subvolume layout of DEVICE by mounting its top level
+#   (subvolid=5) and either (1) reading the layout manifest if present
+#   (authoritative), or (2) discovering the existing subvolumes with
+#   `btrfs subvolume list` and guessing their mountpoints by convention.
+#   Populates btrfs_subvols / btrfs_subvol_mounts (sorted shallow-first so
+#   parent mounts precede children) and btrfs_root_subvol / btrfs_layout_source.
+#   Returns 0 if any subvolumes were found (=> subvol mode), 1 otherwise.
+load_btrfs_layout () {
+	local _dev="$1" _tmp _raw="" _src="default" _rc=1 _sv _mp _i
+	_tmp=$(mktemp -d)
+	mount -o subvolid=5 "$_dev" "$_tmp" 2>/dev/null || { rmdir "$_tmp"; return 1; }
+	if [[ -f "$_tmp/$btrfs_layout_manifest" ]]; then
+		_raw=$(awk -F'\t' '/^[[:space:]]*#/{next} NF<2{next} {print $1"\t"$2}' "$_tmp/$btrfs_layout_manifest")
+		_src="manifest"
+	else
+		_raw=$(btrfs subvolume list "$_tmp" 2>/dev/null | awk '{print $NF}' \
+			| while read -r _s; do
+				[[ "$_s" == */* ]] && continue   # skip nested subvolumes
+				printf '%s\t%s\n' "$_s" "$(btrfs_guess_mount "$_s")"
+			done)
+		_src="guessed"
+	fi
+	umount "$_tmp" 2>/dev/null; rmdir "$_tmp"
+
+	if [[ -n "$_raw" ]]; then
+		btrfs_subvols=(); btrfs_subvol_mounts=()
+		while IFS=$'\t' read -r _ _sv _mp; do
+			[[ -z "$_sv" || -z "$_mp" ]] && continue
+			btrfs_subvols+=("$_sv"); btrfs_subvol_mounts+=("$_mp")
+		done < <(printf '%s\n' "$_raw" | awk -F'\t' 'NF>=2 && $2!="" {d=gsub(/\//,"/",$2); print d"\t"$1"\t"$2}' | sort -n -k1,1)
+		if [[ ${#btrfs_subvols[@]} -gt 0 ]]; then
+			btrfs_root_subvol="@rootfs"
+			for _i in "${!btrfs_subvols[@]}"; do
+				[[ "${btrfs_subvol_mounts[$_i]}" == "/" ]] && btrfs_root_subvol="${btrfs_subvols[$_i]}"
+			done
+			btrfs_layout_source="$_src"
+			_rc=0
+		fi
+	fi
+	return $_rc
+}
+
 if [[ -f $configfile ]]; then
     source $configfile
 else
